Here are the MSTest patterns for each scenario:

### 1. Windows-only tests

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[OSCondition(OperatingSystems.Windows)]
// Or, if using plain MSTest without a custom attribute:
[TestMethod]
[TestCategory("WindowsOnly")]
public void Registry_ReadsExpectedValue()
{
    if (!OperatingSystem.IsWindows())
    {
        Assert.Inconclusive("Requires Windows.");
        return;
    }
    // ... registry code
}
```

### 2. Skip in CI (requires local GPU)

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Render_ProducesExpectedOutput()
{
    if (Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("CI") is not null)
    {
        Assert.Inconclusive("Skipped in CI — requires a local GPU.");
        return;
    }
    // ... GPU test
}
```

`Assert.Inconclusive` marks the test as **skipped/warning** rather than pass or fail, so your CI pipeline stays green while clearly flagging why it didn't run.

### 3. Flaky external API — retry with `[TestCategory]`

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[TestCategory("Flaky")]
[Timeout(15000)] // guard against hung HTTP calls
public void Weather_ReturnsForecast()
{
    // Option A: retry loop inside the test
    const int maxRetries = 3;
    for (int i = 0; i < maxRetries; i++)
    {
        try
        {
            var result = WeatherClient.GetForecast("Seattle");
            Assert.IsNotNull(result);
            return; // success
        }
        catch (HttpRequestException) when (i < maxRetries - 1)
        {
            Thread.Sleep(1000 * (i + 1)); // back off
        }
    }
}
```

You can then **exclude** flaky tests from your main CI gate:

```bash
dotnet test --filter "TestCategory!=Flaky"
```

### 4. Cleanup even on failure — use `[TestCleanup]`

```csharp
[TestClass]
public class TempFileTests
{
    private string? _tempFile;

    [TestInitialize]
    public void Setup()
    {
        _tempFile = Path.GetTempFileName();
    }

    [TestCleanup] // Runs after EVERY test, even if it throws
    public void Cleanup()
    {
        if (_tempFile is not null && File.Exists(_tempFile))
            File.Delete(_tempFile);
    }

    [TestMethod]
    public void ProcessFile_WritesExpectedContent()
    {
        File.WriteAllText(_tempFile!, "test data");
        var result = MyProcessor.Process(_tempFile!);
        Assert.AreEqual("expected", result);
        // If this assert fails, [TestCleanup] still deletes the file
    }
}
```

### Quick reference

| Scenario | Mechanism |
|---|---|
| OS-specific | `Assert.Inconclusive` guard / custom condition attribute |
| Skip in CI | Check `CI` env var → `Assert.Inconclusive` |
| Flaky / external | `[TestCategory("Flaky")]` + retry loop + `[Timeout]` |
| Guaranteed cleanup | `[TestCleanup]` (runs even on failure) |

`[TestCleanup]` is the MSTest equivalent of a `finally` block at the test level — it's the idiomatic way to handle resource teardown. For class-wide resources, the analogous pair is `[ClassInitialize]` / `[ClassCleanup]`.
